post_text:
We have great news for our families! Free meals for students are continuing via our Grab & Go service.

The U.S. Department of Agriculture announced last week it will extend funding for student meals, so we are again offering Grab & Go meals at select school sites throughout the district.

Meals are available at no charge to Peninsula School District students 18 years and younger through December 2020, depending on federal funding. This is a change to what we previously shared regarding meals for the 2020-2021 school year.

We still encourage families to submit free and reduced meal price applications, if appropriate. Find further information, including meal sites and routes information, at http://ow.ly/fTKh50BmiO6.

post_text:
We're excited to announce that students in grades K-1 will be invited to attend school in-person starting Monday, Sept. 21.

Pierce County's COVID-19 case rates have recently moved to the Moderate range, allowing our youngest learners back into classrooms for in-person instruction. This plan assumes Pierce County COVID-19 case rates continue to be stable or decrease.

K-1 families who do not wish to send their students in-person will have the option to continue with remote learning.

See a video announcement from Superintendent Dr. Art Jarvis at http://ow.ly/1dQA50BiKJF and read more at www.psd401.net/schoolreopening. Please send questions to info@psd401.net or contact your school principal.

shared_text:
Peninsula School District - Human Resources Department
July 7 at 3:06 PM ·

Employment Opportunity - School Bus Driver Training Program
Now Hiring - Substitute Bus Drivers:

Summer Session Training Class begins August 3rd, 2020
Apply Online: https://www.psd401.net/departments/human-resources

- Must be 21 Years of Age
- Licensed Driver for at Least 5 Years
- Includes 3-6 weeks of Paid Training
- Driver's Abstract, Fingerprint Background Check, Drug & Alcohol Testing, First Aid/CPR Certificate, DOT physical, and CDL test will be paid for and provided by Peninsula School District

This position safely operates school buses under all types of weather conditions, including, but not limited to fog, rain, sleet, snow, and ice. Responsibilities include transporting students and other authorized persons over regular "to and from school" routes, field trips, co-curricular activities, and special or extra activity trips as authorized by the school district officials.

A reminder for today's Summer Send Off. Our transportation team and other staff will be on the road today (Friday, June 19) to greet students, families and community members and wish them well for the summer.

post_text: Are you a family who lives within PSD boundaries and needs food assistance? Please email info@foodbackpacks4kids.org for more information. Thank you for all you do Food Backpacks 4 Kids!
shared_text:
Food Backpacks 4 Kids
May 23 at 3:19 PM ·

Saturday vibes. We welcomed the sun and our FB4K families with open arms. We were handing out smiles and air hugs along with some cheese, bananas, apples, masks, body wash, chips and a whole lot of food.
The bottom photo shows a few of the 50 boxes of food we are providing to families each week.

If you have children enrolled in the Peninsula School District or homeschool and live within the school district boundaries and need food assistance, email info@foodbackpacks4kids.org to start the sign up process.

post_text: Thank you Food Backpacks 4 Kids and volunteers for the amazing work you are doing in our community!
shared_text:
Food Backpacks 4 Kids
April 24 at 7:07 AM ·

Wednesday was a busy day. We went home tired, but with our hearts full of joy. Our volunteers helped us unload and shelve over 1,700 lbs of donated food from the community and our bi-weekly delivery from the Emergency Food Network. They also prepared boxes and bags for our partners in Communities In Schools of Peninsula and Peninsula School District who help deliver to families with transportation issues. And they set up the site for our food backpacking day on Friday. No wonder they are tired. 😁

Thank you volunteers and thank you to our community for your support.

Volunteers standing closer than 6 feet apart are within the same household.

And our site pups, Kona and Rusey, dropped in for the photo op.

post_text: Written by one of our very own! Nicely done, Tate McReynolds!
shared_text:
Washington Interscholastic Activities Association
March 31 at 10:00 AM ·

READ: "Dear Class of 2020," by Tate McReynolds, a senior at Gig Harbor High School.

http://wiaa.com/Blog.aspx?BID=3

In our latest student story about how the COVID-19 shutdown is impacting students around the state, Tate offers some advice to her fellow seniors:

"We never thought our senior year of high school would end up like this. It could’ve happened anywhere, anytime, but it happened to us. And I’d like to think it happened to us for a reason. We’re a part of something bigger than ourselves now - something we’ll look back on at our high school reunions, and realize that all we’re missing out on now, is the hope for our future. My advice to other high school seniors: Make the most of the situation we’re in, because we’re in it for a reason."

Click the link above to read Tate's story and to learn about how you can share yours.

post_text: We know some parents have been asking about AP. Please see the latest from the College Board.
shared_text:
The College Board
March 20 at 10:24 AM ·

We know the coronavirus has created challenges for AP students and teachers. Here’s how the College Board will support you during this time:

1️⃣ We’re providing free, live and on-demand AP courses

To support AP students affected by school closures due to COVID-19, students and schools will have access to live AP review lessons, delivered by AP teachers from across the country. Lessons will begin March 25.

2️⃣ We’re developing a new at-home testing option

Because of the challenges created by COVID-19, we’re developing a new at-home AP Exam option. Students will be able to test on a computer, tablet, or smartphone.

We will invest so that every AP student impacted by COVID-19 has the tools and connectivity they need to review AP content online and take the exam from home.

During this challenging time, we will work to give every AP student the opportunity to earn the college credit and placement they’ve been working toward all year while maintaining a focus on the health and safety of our AP community.

More details here: http://spr.ly/61851tbn3.

post_text:
Dear school volunteers and community partners,

The closure of our schools for a minimum of six weeks will be disruptive to our students, families and community, to a degree we have never experienced.

The charge to districts across the state is for us to help our community in new ways. This includes ensuring food for families, childcare for health workers and first responders, and continuing learning opportunities for students.

This is clearly new ground for all of us. Working together, with our community partners and volunteers, is what makes our community so special. And working together through this effort will be no different.

In these early days, we are assessing our needs and priorities. Many of you have reached out to see how you can help, and while we don’t have clear answers yet, we are looking forward to working with you and uplifting our community together.

Check back for updates at psd401.net/covid19.

post_text: Pierce County will continue work this week to install a new traffic signal near PHS, possibly causing delays.
shared_text:
Pierce County Planning & Public Works
February 8 at 8:50 AM ·

Update: The signal will be activated Feb. 19 (weather dependent).

Work on a project to improve the 62nd Ave. NW and 144th St. NW intersection by Peninsula High School will resume next week, with crews installing components of the new traffic signal system. We expect to activate the new signal the week of Feb. 17 (Peninsula School District's mid-winter break). We will provide an update when we have the activation date.

There may be alternating one-way traffic along both 62nd Ave. NW and 144th St. NW between 9:15 a.m. and 2 p.m. on weekdays during this work. General work hours are 7 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. on weekdays.

Final pavement work is expected to take place in mid-2020.

Learn more about the project at www.piercecountywa.gov/crp5801.

CC: Peninsula School District

An Educational Programs and Operations Replacement Levy will be on the Feb 11 ballot to replace a levy approved by voters in 2016.

The district relies on local residents to regularly renew levies to fund critical areas, such as teachers and support staff, athletics and extracurricular activities, safety and security, professional development for staff, and preventative routine maintenance projects.

This funding maintains important programs, operations and support.

This funding maintains important programs, operations and support.

post_text:
We appreciate our substitutes!
Lynn Grinnell has been a substitute teacher in the Peninsula School District for about 5 years, primarily at Voyager Elementary. She has also subbed at Purdy Elementary, Minter Creek Elementary and Kopachuck Middle School.

"I love the flexibility, and I love seeing the kids," Grinnell said. "I'm in the same classrooms a lot so I really get to know the kids, and I love seeing the progress that they've made." Lynn is a retired teacher and high school administrator. On her days off from teaching, she enjoys training dogs and taking long walks with her dogs. Thank you, Lynn!

#WeArePSD
#PSD401

post_text:
We appreciate our substitutes! Jerry Guardanapo has been a substitute bus driver for more than 5 years and has driven most routes throughout the district. Lately he’s been subbing most days, “because they need me,” he said.

After driving tractor trailers for UPS for 34 years, Jerry wanted to keep moving.

“I like driving, and it’s not me to be sitting down for long periods of time,” Jerry said. “My wife says I failed retirement.” When he’s not driving a bus, he’s powerlifting almost 300 pounds at the gym. “I’m an inspiration to all the seniors.”

#WeArePSD
#PSD401

Kicking off 2nd quarter of our Social Media Fish Bowl for Peninsula High School is Victoria Christiansen.
Victoria spent her career in forestry and now holds the top job in the nation in her field.
“My years at Peninsula High School were incredibly valuable, formative years for me. I was trying to get past my shyness and uncertainties and Peninsula provided a strong sense of
community which was a treasured anchor point for me. Peninsula provided me a place to really be curious and develop a quest for lifelong learning.”
Will the Seahawks prevail? Keep them coming and we'll find out!

post_text:
Kicking off 2nd quarter of our Social Media Fish Bowl is Anna Martin.
Anna attended Artondale, Goodman, and GHHS. Anna comes from a long-time Gig Harbor family. Her parents attended Peninsula and her grandparents attended Union High School (currently the Harbor Ridge location). Not only did she proudly work in the GHHS main office for the last 8 years, but her own children benefited from the amazing staff, strong academics, leadership, drama, debate, music, athletics, and cheer at the school. Though she is a Tide through and through she says, “ I am excited to join the Pioneer staff as the new Office Manager this year. PSD has served my family for so many years, I love being able to give back to our children and look forward to making a difference in new and exciting ways.”
Will the Tides prevail? Let's find out!

#WeArePSD
#PSD401

post_text:
Receive text messages from PSD! To opt in, send a text message of "Y" or "Yes" to 67587. You can opt out of these messages at any time by simply replying to any message with "Stop."

If you receive an error message such as "Denied" - this indicates that you do not have SMS short code turned on in your account. Change that by contacting your cell phone carrier and ask them to turn on SMS short code.

Text notifications may be sent district-wide, such as in an emergency or if schools are delayed or closed due to weather; or, they may be sent to only parents/guardians of an affected building or bus.

#PSD401
#PSDCares

post_text: We are so excited about the improvements this project will bring to our PSD families and our local community. Please keep this important info in mind if you need to travel around this area.
shared_text:
Pierce County Planning & Public Works
October 22, 2019 at 11:29 AM ·

Work at the 62nd Ave. NW and 144th St. NW intersection by the Peninsula High School baseball field continues.

The two roads will be paved within the project area at night Wednesday, Oct. 23 and Thursday, Oct. 24. Work hours will be 6 p.m. Wednesday to 7 a.m. Thursday, and 6 p.m. Thursday to 11 a.m. Friday.

The roads will remain open, although they may be reduced to one lane with alternating traffic during work hours. Motorists should expect minor delays during most of this work. Significant delays are possible during the Friday morning commute. Please use alternative routes during the Friday morning commute.

Roadway striping is expected to take place in the middle of next week. The work is expected to take several hours.

Learn more about this project: www.piercecountywa.gov/crp5801.

CC: Peninsula School District

Here at PSD, we are taking time this October to promote disability etiquette in honor of National Disability Awareness Month. PSD facilitates special education programs district-wide for students ages 3-21. Sensitivity toward people with disabilities benefits students in need of special education services as well as their typically developing peers.
Check out these tips from the United Spinal Association. http://ow.ly/1OsH50wJ04B.

post_text:
Receive text messages from PSD! To opt in, send a text message of "Y" or "Yes" to 67587. You can opt out of these messages at any time by simply replying to any message with "Stop."

If you receive an error message such as "Denied" - this indicates that you do not have SMS short code turned on in your account. Change that by contacting your cell phone carrier and ask them to turn on SMS short code.

Text notifications may be sent district-wide, such as in an emergency or in case of delays or closures due to weather; or, they may be sent to only parents/guardians of an affected building or bus.

Peninsula School District high school students took a bold step into the field of medicine by participating in the district’s fifth annual Summer Health Sciences Internship Program.

Over four days, students participated in career-enhancing activities directed by Gig Harbor Fire & Medic One - Official Site , St. Anthony Hospital in Gig Harbor, Mary Bridge Children's Hospital , and Tacoma Community College . Fifteen students were accepted into the program based on academic performance, interest in medicine, and professional recommendations.

Learn more on our website: http://ow.ly/ktS750v1YQJ

post_text:
PSD is pleased to announce Dr. Joe Potts will be the new principal for Peninsula High School.

Dr. Potts is an experienced high school administrator, having previously served as principal for eight years at Kentlake HS, a diverse 4A high school, and five years as assistant principal at Kentwood HS in the Kent School District. His most recent experience included two years as a superintendent in a small district in Iowa.

Staff and parents of current and incoming PHS students were notified earlier today of Dr. Potts' selection.

Welcome to PSD!

#beawesome #wearepsd

post_text:
We are excited to announce Elementary School #10, located at the former Boys & Girls Club, will be named Pioneer Elementary. The newest elementary school in Peninsula School District will open as a STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Math) school the fall of 2020, as a magnet school for 550 students from across the district.

PSD sought input on the name and theme of the school through surveys and a naming committee, which offered recommendations to the school board.

During the 2019-2020 school year, Pioneer Elementary will immediately alleviate elementary overcrowding by housing fifth grade students from Discovery Elementary and preschool classes from other schools throughout the district.

#thankyouPSDvoters

May 6, 2019 at 5:00 PM ·

Seattle - we are coming back!
Lots of people didn’t get tickets so we will be back on June 8 at 1 pm! Same venue - Chapel Hill Presbyterian Church in Gig Harbor
Tickets go on sale this Wednesday (May 8th) at 5 pm PDT
Event sold out in 5 minutes last time so be ready.
Share this post for a chance to win 2 free tickets (3 winners). Tag all your colleagues for a chance to win tickets for ERYBODY you tag! Winners announced on Wednesday at 4 PM as last comment on this post.

Click here for more info and to grab your tickets:

post_text:
JOIN OUR TEAM

If you enjoy kids and driving, become a school bus driver. Peninsula School District Transportation Department is seeking candidates to become substitute school bus drivers.

Peninsula School Bus Drivers transport over 5,500 students daily and travel more than a million miles per year. We are a great team, who take pride in transporting our students to and from school safely.

We offer a comprehensive paid training program. With completion of our training, you will become a CDL licensed driver and a valuable member of our Transportation Team.

Interviews are being scheduled for the week of July 15th for our summer class.

Class begins July 29th

apply on-line: psd401.net/human-resources

Or call 253-530-3900 for more information

This is a very rewarding occupation and an excellent source of supplemental income.

Peninsula School District
March 4, 2019 at 10:45 AM ·

Why register for Kindergarten now?

*Connect with your new school about exciting upcoming Kindergarten transition events!
*Learn about summer programs to help ease transition.
*Help the district plan for the right number of Kindergarten teachers.

Peninsula School district Offers FREE Full Day Kindergarten for students five days a week at all our Elementary schools. If your child will be 5-years-old on or before August 31st, click the link below to register them for school in the fall.
Here is the link to register:
19-20 English

19-20 Spanish
http://ow.ly/Q67z30nUU3D
Need help with online registration? Here is an informational flyer:
